h issues that remain central to our lives today: the viability of a secular Europe with Enlightenment values coming to terms with a darker view of human nature mass culture and its dangers; the rise of the politics of irrationality identity and the “other” in Western civilization new ways to represent the postwar world the epistemological dilemma in a world of uncertainty; and the new Fascism—was it a new norm or an aberration? Arthur Haberman sees 1930 as a watershed year in the intellectual life of Europe and with this book, the first to see the contributions of the public intellectuals of 1930 as a single entity, he forces a reconsideration and reinterpretation of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIntellectualszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  a1930s.  aAldous Huxley.  aBertolt Brecht.  aEurope between the wars.  aEuropean public intellectuals.  aJose Ortega y Gasset.  aKurt Weill.  aModernism in art and society.  aSigmund Freud.  aThomas Mann.  aVirginia Woolf.  acultural pessimism.  airrationality in politics society.  amass culture.  athe ‘Other’ in the West.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112362440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771123624423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771123624/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles